    "chatHistory": [
      {
        "id": "msg-1",
        "role": "user",
        "type": "text",
        "content": "Rob. $1m borrowing capacity. $100k income. $150k deposit. $50k/year cashflow goal. $2m equity goal. 20 years.",
        "timestamp": 1780280472438
      },
      {
        "id": "msg-3",
        "role": "assistant",
        "type": "text",
        "content": "Built a 5-property plan for Rob across QLD, NSW \u2014 2 regional unit (cashflow) properties, 2 regional house (cashflow) properties, and a commercial (low cost). Modelled at 70-88% LVR with LMI capitalised with IO loans, biased toward cashflow, low price point. For tighter numbers, share monthly_savings.\n\nBased on the inputs, the model shows the plan clearing the $2M target. See the dashboard for the engine's exact projection.",
        "timestamp": 1780280498291
      },
      {
        "id": "msg-4",
        "role": "user",
        "type": "text",
        "content": "What happens to this portfolio if there is a rate rise?",
        "timestamp": 1780280576062
      },
      {
        "id": "msg-6",
        "role": "assistant",
        "type": "text",
        "content": "All five properties are modelled on IO loans, so the portfolio is directly exposed to rate movements \u2014 there is no principal reduction buffering the repayment impact. In the early years the cashflow is already negative (net -$8,329 in 2026, widening to -$22,788 by 2028), so a rate rise would deepen those deficits and increase the monthly holding costs Rob needs to cover from income and savings. The commercial property carries the largest single loan at $525,000, making it the biggest contributor to additional repayment pressure. The key question is how much of a rise \u2014 even 0.5% across $2.08M in total debt (at full acquisition) adds roughly $10,000/year in repayments.",
        "timestamp": 1780280600701,
        "assumptions": [
          "Rate rise impact is directional only \u2014 exact figures depend on the magnitude of the rise and the modelled interest rate",
          "Total debt at full acquisition estimated from sum of individual property loans in the plan"
        ]
      }
    ],
